  <body>
    <Header />
    <ReadingProgressBar />
    <main>
      <article class="article-wrap">
        <header class="article-header">
          <h1>{title}</h1>
          <p class="meta"><FormattedDate date={dateObj} /> · {category}</p>
          <p class="lede">
            The folklore says World Cup third-place games are always a goalfest. All-time, bronze matches and finals average almost the same goals. The real pattern starts in the modern low-scoring knockout era: since 1990 the bronze game stays open while finals and semis tighten.
          </p>
        </header>

        <div class="scoreboard" aria-label="Key goals-per-game figures">
          <div class="stat true">
            <div class="n">3.56</div>
            <div class="l">3rd place GPG<br />1990-2022</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat false">
            <div class="n">2.44</div>
            <div class="l">Final GPG<br />1990-2022</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat neutral">
            <div class="n">2.28</div>
            <div class="l">Semi-final GPG<br />1990-2022</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="n">3.80≈3.81</div>
            <div class="l">All-time 3rd ≈ Final<br />near parity</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_verdict.svg`} alt="Verdict matrix comparing third-place scoring claims" width="800" height="280" loading="eager" />
        </figure>

        <h2>1. Is the high-scoring claim true?</h2>
        <p>
          Popular commentary treats the bronze match as a perpetual open game: loose, almost a friendly. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_place_playoff">Wikipedia’s third-place page</a> calls it “generally a high-scoring affair,” noting that no men’s third-place game has finished under two goals since Poland’s 1-0 over Brazil in 1974. Neutrals get told to tune in for goals.
        </p>
        <p>The careful version needs a comparator. Higher than <em>what</em>?</p>

        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_modern_gpg.svg`} alt="Bar chart of modern goals per game by round" width="720" height="360" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>
        <p class="chart-cap">Modern bronze games sit well above finals, semis, and the tournament average.</p>

        <h3>All-time: the myth meets Opta</h3>
        <p>
          Across 20 men’s World Cup third-place play-offs (1934, 1938, and every edition since 1954), there have been <strong>76 goals</strong>, or <strong>3.80 per game</strong>. That matches <a href="https://theanalyst.com/articles/world-cup-third-place-play-off-stats">Opta Analyst</a>. Across 21 standalone finals, the final sits at about <strong>3.81 goals per game</strong>. All-time, bronze and gold are statistical twins.
        </p>
        <p>
          That fact kills the lazy theory that bronze games score more simply because “nobody defends.” The game with everything on the line has historically leaked just as many goals, often through nerves, open transitions, and high quality rather than indifference.
        </p>

        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_alltime_vs_modern.svg`} alt="All-time versus modern goals per game comparison" width="720" height="360" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <h3>Modern era: the claim becomes true</h3>
        <p>Split the sample at 1990 and the picture flips. From 1990 through 2022:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Third place:</strong> 32 goals in 9 games → <strong>3.56 GPG</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Final:</strong> 22 goals in 9 games → <strong>2.44 GPG</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Semi-finals (sample):</strong> about 2.28 GPG</li>
          <li><strong>Whole-tournament average:</strong> about 2.52 GPG</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Modern finals became cage matches (1990 1-0, 1994 0-0, 2006 1-1, 2010 1-0, 2014 1-0), then reopened in 2018 and 2022. Third-place games never joined the low-scoring winter. They stayed in the 2-5 goal band.
        </p>
        <p>
          Same-year pairing: third place outscored that year’s final in 10 editions, matched it twice, and trailed eight times. Mean difference is small all-time (+0.10), but the modern gap is structural, not noise.
        </p>

        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_same_year.svg`} alt="Line chart of same-year third place versus final goals" width="900" height="340" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>
        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_timeline.svg`} alt="Timeline of third-place match goal totals" width="900" height="320" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>
        <p class="chart-cap">Since 1974, every bronze game has produced at least two goals. Four of the last seven (from 1994) hit four or more.</p>

        <div class="callouts">
          <div class="callout">
            <h4>Floor effect</h4>
            <p>No men’s bronze match under two goals since 1974. The “goalfest” story has a hard floor even when it is not a shootout.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="callout note">
            <h4>Vs tournament average</h4>
            <p>Third place beat that edition’s overall GPG in 15 of 20 years. The excess is largest in tight modern Cups (2010: +2.7).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="callout warn">
            <h4>Counterevidence</h4>
            <p>All-time parity with finals. Early 1-0 bronzes (1962-74). Managers often publicly hate the fixture.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2>2. What the numbers say about “openness”</h2>
        <p>
          Goals alone can mislead. Opta’s expected-goals read (1966-2022, excluding own goals) shows third-place games produced 50 goals from 52.8 xG, a mild underperformance of about <strong>−0.19 per game</strong>. That is the <em>smallest</em> shortfall of any World Cup round. Finals underperform by about −0.60 per game; last-16 matches by −0.79.
        </p>
        <p>
          Translation: bronze games convert chance quality almost normally. Finals and early knockouts leave more goals on the table, consistent with choke, ultra-conservative game states, and inspired goalkeeping under maximum stakes.
        </p>

        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_xg.svg`} alt="Horizontal bars of xG underperformance by World Cup round" width="720" height="340" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <p>
          Lineup policy reinforces the openness story without requiring players to “not try.” From 2006-2022, managers averaged <strong>3.9 starting XI changes</strong> for the third-place match, versus 1.5 into a semi-final and only 0.6 into a final. Fringe attackers, backup full-backs, and less rehearsed defensive units share the pitch. That is not pure exhibition chaos. It is a designed reduction in continuity that raises variance and, historically, goals.
        </p>

        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_lineup.svg`} alt="Bar chart of average starting lineup changes by match type" width="720" height="360" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <h2>3. Psychology and strategy: why the game opens up</h2>
        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_mechanism.svg`} alt="Mechanism cascade from semi-final loss to higher scoring" width="900" height="200" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <h3>A. Asymmetric stakes after the semi-final</h3>
        <p>
          Both teams arrive having just lost the match that mattered most. The World Cup is gone. What remains is ordinal pride: third versus fourth, bronze medals versus none, a modest prize-money bump, ranking points, and a last televised ninety minutes of a career-defining summer.
        </p>
        <p>
          Prospect theory predicts people weigh losses more heavily than equivalent gains. Here the catastrophic loss already happened in the semi. Relative to that reference point, the bronze match is a small gain domain. Teams can take offensive risk without reopening the wound of elimination. The cost of a mistake is no longer “we are out.” It is “we finish fourth instead of third.”
        </p>

        <h3>B. Counterfactual emotion: bronze versus silver</h3>
        <p>
          <a href="https://doi.org/10.1037/0022-3514.69.4.603">Medvec, Madey, and Gilovich’s 1995 study</a> of Olympic medalists found bronze medalists often looked happier than silver medalists. Silver invites an upward counterfactual (“I almost won”). Bronze invites a downward one (“I almost left with nothing”). The third-place playoff literature cites the same pattern for playoff bronze winners versus final losers.
        </p>
        <p>
          That research is about post-event affect, but it maps cleanly onto in-match motivation: the bronze game is the live opportunity to secure the “at least we got something” story. Fourth place is pure void. That discrete cliff (medal vs no medal) is sharper than the continuous gap between first and second once the final is under way.
        </p>

        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_psychology.svg`} alt="Silver versus bronze counterfactual psychology diagram" width="800" height="260" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>

        <h3>C. Reduced defensive obligation, not zero effort</h3>
        <p>
          The folklore says players stop defending. The data says they stop defending <em>as if a single error ends a lifetime goal</em>. Finals compress risk: one transition can write history. Bronze games still have professional pride (Croatia 2022 celebrated like a title; Germany 2006 treated the home bronze as a national event; Turkey and South Korea 2002 both wanted the podium).
        </p>
        <p>
          But the optimal strategy tilts toward initiative. Sitting deep for a 0-0 that might go to extra time is less attractive when everyone wants the plane home. The third-place match has <strong>never gone to penalties</strong> and only once to extra time (France 4-2 Belgium, 1986). That is consistent with teams preferring open resolution over attritional stalemate.
        </p>

        <h3>D. Individual incentives punch above team stakes</h3>
        <p>
          Goals in the bronze game count for the Golden Boot. Fontaine’s four in 1958 sealed a still-standing 13-goal tournament record. Schillaci (1990), Šuker (1998), and Müller (2010) padded winning tallies here. Eusébio scored in 1966. Attackers have a private reason to stay vertical even if the collective mood is flat. That misalignment (team grief, striker ambition) is a feature of open games.
        </p>

        <h3>E. Money is real, the delta is small</h3>
        <figure class="chart">
          <img src={`${img}/chart_prize.svg`} alt="Prize money bars for first through fourth place" width="720" height="360" loading="lazy" />
        </figure>
        <p>
          In 2026 reporting, third place sits near <strong>$29 million</strong> and fourth near <strong>$27 million</strong> (<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/7447101/2026/07/16/how-much-prize-money-is-won-at-the-world-cup/">Athletic prize breakdown</a>). Champions take about $50 million. Two million dollars is not nothing for federations, yet it is a rounding error beside the reputational gap between finalist and also-ran. Money keeps the fixture from pure farce. It does not explain a +1 goal gap versus modern finals. Pride, medals, rankings, and individual awards do more work.
        </p>

        <h3>F. Heterogeneous motivation</h3>
        <p>
          Match histories show uneven seriousness. Heavy favorites who “should” have been in the final sometimes rest stars (Platini skipped France’s 1982 and 1986 bronze games). Cinderella sides treat bronze as history (Sweden 1994 parade; Croatia 1998 and 2022; Turkey 2002). When at least one side needs the podium narrative, the game stays competitive. When both sides rotate heavily, variance still rises because organization drops.
        </p>

        <blockquote>
          <p>“I think this match should never be played… The worst thing is that there is a chance you are going to lose twice in a row.” - Louis van Gaal, 2014</p>
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          <p>“It’s not a game any team wants to play in.” - Gareth Southgate, 2018</p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
          Managers’ contempt coexists with watchable football. Players may not want the fixture, yet once it starts, professional identity and public scoreboard take over. <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/7442598/2026/07/15/world-cup-third-place-playoff-explainer/">The Athletic’s 2026 explainer</a> tracks the same manager quotes and the goalfest reputation for neutrals.
        </p>

        <h2>4. Strategy board: what coaches actually optimize</h2>
        <div class="two">
          <div>
            <h3>Final optimization</h3>
            <p>Max continuity (0.6 XI changes). Risk of historic failure dominates. Game states become low-event. Set pieces and transitional moments decide. Underperformance vs xG is large.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Bronze optimization</h3>
            <p>Reward squad (3.9 changes). Avoid injuries before club season. Win bronze if possible. Let attackers hunt personal tallies. Accept open structure; avoid pointless extra time.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>
          Those two objective functions produce different football even with the same talent tier (both teams were good enough to reach the last four). Semi-finals sit closer to finals on scoring because the prize is still the final itself. Once that prize vanishes, the constraint set changes in a single matchday.
        </p>

        <h2>5. Full bronze scoreboard</h2>
        <p>Complete men’s third-place results, compiled from <a href="https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/49385575/third-place-matches-men-world-cup-winners-results">ESPN’s results list</a> and historical tournament records:</p>
        <div style="overflow-x:auto">
          <table class="data">
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Year</th><th>Winner</th><th>Score</th><th>Loser</th><th>Goals</th></tr>
            </thead>
