        <h2>6. Women’s World Cup: weaker pattern</h2>
        <p>
          With fewer editions, women’s third-place games are mixed: several 2-0 or 1-0 results, a 0-0 (1999, pens), and England’s 2015 extra-time win over Germany. The “always a goalfest” slogan is a men’s modern-era story more than a universal football law. Small samples and different competitive density matter. Treat women’s bronze scoring as a separate series, not a confirmation.
        </p>

        <h2>7. Synthesis</h2>
        <div class="verdict-box">
          <p>
            <strong>Third-place World Cup games are not magically higher scoring than finals across history (3.80 vs 3.81).</strong>
            They <strong>are</strong> reliably higher scoring than modern finals, modern semis, and typical tournament averages, because after semi-final elimination the remaining incentives (bronze vs nothing, medals, modest money, rankings, Golden Boot) reward initiative while lineup rotation and lower choke pressure raise variance and finishing efficiency.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h3>What to believe, ranked</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Strongly supported:</strong> modern (1990+) bronze GPG exceeds final and semi GPG; no bronze under two goals since 1974; heavy rotation is real; xG conversion is freer than in finals.</li>
          <li><strong>Well supported:</strong> salvage psychology and medal counterfactuals shape motivation; individual awards pull attackers forward; FIFA keeps the game for spectacle, revenue, and classification.</li>
          <li><strong>Weak / false:</strong> “always higher than the final”; “players do not try at all”; “money is the main driver of the $2m delta.”</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>8. What this means for watching</h2>
        <p>
          If you want the purest high-stakes chess, watch the final. If you want last-four talent with fewer handbrakes, the bronze match is often the better neutrals’ game in the modern era. Expect rotated XIs, early goals (Sükür’s 11-second record still stands from 2002), and a non-trivial chance of three or more goals. Do not expect both managers to pretend they are happy to be there.
        </p>
        <p>
          The product on the pitch is a compromise between grief and professionalism, and that compromise, measured carefully, scores.
        </p>

        <h2>9. Alternative explanations that fail</h2>
        <p>
          “Indifferent defending alone” fails the all-time test: finals match bronze for goals historically. “It’s just an exhibition” fails when hosts and Cinderella nations treat bronze as national memory. “Fatigue makes defending worse” should also suppress attacking coordination; instead xG conversion is cleaner than in finals. “The ball or era scoring environment” cannot explain within-tournament gaps: the same ball and rules produce 1-0 finals and 3-2 bronzes weeks apart.
        </p>
        <p>
          A better multi-cause model is additive. Start with last-four talent. Remove title stakes. Add rotation. Add private attacker incentives. Add a discrete bronze cliff versus fourth. The sum is modern high-event football without requiring anyone to stop caring.
        </p>
        <p>
          Do not pool 1958’s 6-3 with 2010’s 3-2 and call it one phenomenon. Pre-1970s football was a different scoring regime. The interesting causal window is post-1990, when knockout football generally tightened and the bronze match refused to follow.
        </p>

